feedback: I just tried to memorize from the first round which one they belonged to.
I tried to remember the pictures i seen in the trails.
I noticed that the one that had all 3 was usually 1 and the one on the left side was also usually 1. The right side was usually 2.
Objects with 1 feature were more likely to be from family 2. Objects with more than 1 feature were more likely to be from family 1.
Having 3 figures means it belongs to Class 1. Having 1 figure usually means it belongs to Class 2.
1 part belonged to 2, all 3 parts belonged to 1, 2 parts went to both 1 and 2.
I knew singles were almost always 2 and triples were almost always one and had an inkling that doubles had a slight chance to be the same family as what came before.
all 3 was 1, 3 only was 2, 2 and 3 was 2, 2 only was 2, everything else was 1
I assumed that shapes with more than one feature were more likely to be family one and shapes with only 1 feature were more likely to be family 2
I noticed that feature 2 and feature 3 were on family 2 and family 1 had all features the most. I used that while categorizes.

Family 1 seemed to favor having 2 or 3 features, while family 2 much more often had only one. Thus I went by that mostly, but since there were the occasional ones that did not fit that pattern, I also randomly said some of each were in the opposite family from what they seemed to me to be more likely a member of... if that makes sense.
I just tried to notice differences.
I was using a pattern I thought I would see
I just tried to recreate the patterns I had seen in the trial.  I noticed which patterns are always 1 or 2 and what is the frequency of the alternate patterns.
It seemed like both families had equal amounts of the same figures so I try to use both families equal times.
I just did my best to see what grouing went with 1 or 2 the most from the practice session and applied that to the test
When it had all three features it was probably family 1, when it had only 1 feature it was probably family 2
Where they're positioned.

Most of the patterns could have belonged to either family. When all of the panels were present, it was usually family 1. Single panels could be either, though panels leaning towards the right seemed more indicative of family 2, in the examples.
If it had one feature, I selected 2.  If it had more than one feature, I selected 1.  For the most part....
they seemed to point either left or right
The only pattern I really noticed was that it was more likely to be 1 if all three features were present and more likely to be 2 if only one feature was present.
I tried to pay attention to the shapes in the practice round and get a feel for which ones belonged to which family.
I just tried to distinguish what was the most common in one family
I looked at the amount of features the image had and sorted based on my observations during the example.
